Document Type:FBIS TRENDS-9MAR94-JAPAN 
<H3> <TI>      MITI Moving Away From Voluntary Export Restraints </TI></H3>


</HEADER>


<TEXT>
In     an apparent effort to demonstrate that Japan is advancing 
toward full compliance with GATT rules, Japan's Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) is reportedly moving away 
from bilateral voluntary export restraints on textiles and toward 
adoption of more fixed textile import restrictions based on the 
Multilateral Fiber Agreement.  According to the 17 February Nihon 
Keizai Shimbun, MITI is currently formulating the criteria it 
plans to use to justify restrictions on future textile imports 
from China, Pakistan, and Taiwan as early as May 1994.  MITI is 
also reportedly planning for the first time to apply dumping 
duties consistent with GATT rules to textile products and is, 
according to the 18 February Mainichi Shimbun, investigating the 
alleged dumping of Pakistani cotton yarn based on a complaint 
filed by the Japan Spinners' Association in December 1993. 

   MITI is also reportedly considering whether to move away from 
voluntary export restraints in other sectors, such as automobiles 
and forklifts, where Japan has agreed to limit its own exports. 
According to the 21 January Asahi Shimbun, MITI is officially 
maintaining that it has not decided whether the current voluntary 
restraints for car exports to the United States will be renewed. 
However, it reportedly wants to abolish such restraints, 
calculating that now, when Japanese car exports to the United 
States are down, would be a good time to abolish the voluntary 
export restraints for automobiles. 
(AUTHOR:  INNES.  QUESTIONS AND/OR COMMENTS, PLEASE CALL CHIEF, 
ASIA DIVISION ANALYSIS TEAM, (703) 733-6534.) 
EAG/BIETZ/CL 9/2118Z MAR 

