Document Type:FBIS TRENDS-09MAR94-DPRK-ROK 
<H3> <TI>      North Depicts Moves to Avoid Deadlock in Talks </TI></H3>


</HEADER>


<TEXT>
Seeking     to project a conciliatory stance on North-South talks, 
Pyongyang used the 9 March inter-Korean talks to create the image 
that it is making constructive proposals to pave the way for the 
exchange of special envoys, a step that is related to the 
resumption of talks with Washington on the nuclear issue. 
According to Pyongyang television on 9 March, the North Korean 
side advanced a new proposal for the envoy exchange that it 
claimed incorporated South Korean views on the issue.  (The 
proposal, which prescribes the composition of the special envoy's 
entourage, travel arrangements, and other procedural matters, was 
characterized by the South Korean chief delegate as "a positive 
sign," according to Seoul's government-run KBS-1 radio.) 
Nevertheless, clinging to a position that could enable North 
Korea to control the pace of progress at the talks, Pyongyang 
television also depicted the North as still insisting on the four 
basic demands it previously advanced as conditions for exchanging 
envoys. 
   In a gesture that could facilitate an eventual compromise on its 
demands, Pyongyang has slightly tempered its personal attacks on 
ROK President Kim Yong-sam.  A 9 March KCNA report of a Nodong 
Sinmun commentary criticizing Kim's recent remarks on North-South 
relations referred to him as a "traitor" only once, while using 
more neutral terms such as "South Korean rulers" and the "Kim 
Yong-sam group" to refer to the ROK government.  Both sides are 
set to meet again on 12 March. 
   (AUTHOR:  YIM.  QUESTIONS/COMMENTS, PLEASE CALL CHIEF, ASIA 
DIVISION ANALYSIS TEAM, (703) 733-6534.) 
EAG/BIETZ JEG 10/0005Z MAR 

</TEXT>

