Article Type:FBIS 
DUE TO COPYRIGHT OR OTHER RESTRICTIONS THE FOLLOWING 
ITEM IS INTENDED FOR USE ONLY BY U.S. GOVERNMENT 
CONSUMERS. IT IS BASED ON FOREIGN MEDIA CONTENT AND 
BEHAVIOR AND IS ISSUED WITHOUT COORDINATION WITH OTHER 
U.S. GOVERNMENT COMPONENTS. 
Document Type:FBIS TRENDS-10MAR94-ISRAEL 
<H3> <TI>      Rabin, Peres Hint At Dismantling Settlements </TI></H3>


</HEADER>


<TEXT>
In     the wake of the Hebron massacre, both Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin and Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres have hinted that the 
Israeli Government is laying the groundwork for dismantling a few 
controversial Jewish settlements.  Both leaders appear concerned 
to present any such action as a unilateral Israeli decision to 
head off criticism that they are bowing to Palestinian demands on 
the settlements, an issue which was to have been deferred to 
final status negotiations under the Israel-PLO Declaration of 
Principles (DOP).  Rabin seemed deliberately vague in a recent 
interview when asked if he favored moving settlers from the town 
of Hebron, where several small settler enclaves have become a 
focus of attention following the massacre.  He first said "I will 
not answer" the question, then went on to point out that the DOP 
did not call for moving settlements during the current phase of 
negotiations.  Therefore, he continued, there is no requirement 
to move any settlers "on the basis of the negotiations with the 
PLO" and the matter is "currently not on the agenda" of the 
negotiations, a position that seemed to leave open the 
possibility of action taken outside the framework of Israel- 
Palestinian talks.  Rabin also hinted that he is willing to 
negotiate with Yasir 'Arafat over the PLO leader's demand for an 
armed international observer force in the occupied territories, 
twice telling his interviewer "I do not conduct negotiations with 
['Arafat] through you" when pressed on the matter (IDF radio, 8 
March). 

   Peres, who prior to the massacre had openly questioned the 
justification for preserving a small settlement in the Gaza 
Strip, (Qol Yisra'el radio, 12 February) reportedly echoed 
Rabin's remarks on settlements in speaking with journalists on 8 
March.  As reported by The Jerusalem Post the next day, he said 
that "public opinion must be prepared for the possible 
dismantling of some settlements," but that the question of 
settlements "is an internal Israeli affair" and "completely 
divorced from the current negotiations with the PLO."  He 
explained that the Israeli Government had insisted on deferring 
the settlement issue to final status negotiations while 
negotiating the DOP in order to minimize public opposition to the 
DOP.  The government, he said, would "seek to convince the 
public" that evacuating some settlements "needs to be done," but 
"it cannot come as a result of PLO demands." 

(AUTHOR: MORTON.  OUESTIONS AND/OR COMMENTS, PLEASE CALL CHIEF, 
NEAR EAST ANALYSIS BRANCH  (703) 733-6094). 
ENEAG/BLOUGH/JF 10/1914Z MAR 

</TEXT>

