Document Type:FBIS TRENDS-16MAR94-CHINA-FRANCE 
<H3> <TI>      Beijing Strengthens Aviation Ties with Airbus </TI></H3>

</HEADER>


<TEXT>
Continuing     earlier signs that Beijing would reward France for its 
accommodating stance on Taiwan arms sales by expanding Sino- 
French aviation cooperation, Beijing has recently announced 
contracts with the French-based European consortium Airbus 
Industrie (Xinhua, 4,6 March).  According to a Xinhua report of 6 
March, Airbus has reached an agreement worth "tens of millions of 
U.S. dollars" with China Aviation Supplies Corporation for 
production of aircraft parts in a move that reportedly will 
"increase Airbus' share in the potentially huge China market." 
Xinhua also reported on 4 March that Chinese airlines have 
recently announced plans to purchase nine aircraft from Airbus 
(Xinhua, March 4).  Following the restoration of bilateral ties 
in January, and a French pledge to reverse France's previous 
policy of selling arms to Taiwan, China awarded a major subway 
contract to a French firm.  Beijing had previously shunned French 
companies to protest a November 1992 French decision to sell 
Mirage jet fighters to Taiwan. 
(AUTHOR: SIMON. QUESTIONS AND/OR COMMENTS, PLEASE CALL CHIEF, 
CHINA ANALYSIS TEAM, (703)733-6097.) 
EAG/BIETZ/CB 16/1608z Mar 

